HEADWORD: Impaste
<hw>Im*paste"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Impasted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Impasting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>im-</ets> in +
<ets>paste</ets>: cf. It. <ets>impastare</ets>, OF. <ets>empaster</ets>,
F. <ets>emp⟦acir⟧ter</ets>. See 1st <er>In-</er> and
<er>Paste</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To knead; to make into paste; to
concrete.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Blood . . . baked and <xex>impasted</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>To lay color on canvas by
uniting them skillfully together. Cf. <er>Impasto</er>.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impasting</ent>⟦br⟧
